			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I can't condone the original poster's use of the caps lock key, nor his excessive profanity.
<br />

<br />
But, he does make a good point; aside from the more fundamentally disturbing issue of Spec using this supposed tragic death (I'm still a bit uncertain-- perhaps hopeful-- that it may turn out to be untrue) to further a political agenda.
<br />

<br />
Now, the belief is certainly a reasonable one at its core; that stronger gun regulation may have prevented this death, or at the very least, may prevent deaths in the future.
<br />

<br />
But it is always wise to take anything with a grain of salt, and paint it in a scientific matter.
<br />

<br />
Let us go then, to Spec's native Australia.  Australia's crime rate is significantly lower the the US's, and they have some of the most stringent gun laws of any country.  So, it's no surprise that Spec is shocked, just as we all are, over this crime.
<br />

<br />
However, in reality, crime is not so easy to control.  Crime is a combination of two things: motive plus opportunity.  What gun control does is tries to take away from the second part of this, as guns are the means to which a crime can be committed.
<br />

<br />
I wish that worked-- I really do.  As I said though, it's not so easy.
<br />

<br />
Let's go back to Spec's native Australia, which in 1997 instigated a gun ban and buy back program, which is one of the most restrictive in the world.  Here's what happened homicides in the land down under:
<br />

<br />
Year	Homicide 	Assault 	Sexual assault 	Robbery
<br />
1995 	356 	101,710 	13,099 	14,564
<br />
1996 	350 	114,156 	14,542 	16,372
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">1997 	360 	124,500 	14,353 	21,305</span>
<br />
1998 	332 	130,903 	14,336 	23,801
<br />
1999 	386 	134,271 	14,104 	22,606
<br />
2000 	346 	141,124 	15,630 	23,314
<br />
2001 	340 	151,753 	16,744 	26,565
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">(source: <a href="http://www.aic.gov.au/publications/facts/2002/tab01a.html)" target="_blank">http://www.aic.gov.au/publications/facts/2002/tab01a.html)</a></span>
<br />

<br />
If gun control worked as promised, the post-97 rates should be lower, and not higher, than the years pre-97 when guns were more available.
<br />

<br />
But that isn't so.
<br />

<br />
And this is reflected elsewhere as well.
<br />

<br />
Another excellent case in point is Britain.  Britain, much like Spec's Australia, under the leadership of Tony Blair's labor party, instituted a similarily harsh gun control ban.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
During the period 1998-2000, Britain went from fifth to fourth worst in the world league table. An analysis of total recorded crime figures before 1998 also suggests that England and Wales have moved sharply up the league table since Labour came to power in 1997. Crimes fell from 5.5 million in 1993 to 4.5 million in 1997. By 1999, total crimes had risen again to 5.3 million.
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">(http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2002/12/01/ncrime01.xml&sSheet=/news/2002/12/01/ixhome.html)</span>
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
The report from the Centre for Defence Studies at King's College, London, <span style="font-weight: bold">found no link between the legal possession of guns and their use by criminals.</span>
<br />

<br />
Its findings appeared to support the position taken by pistol shooters when their sport was banned in 1997 in response to the murder of 16 Dunblane schoolchildren and their teacher by Thomas Hamilton.
<br />

<br />
More than 160,000 handguns were surrendered to the police. But in the two years after the ban the number of crimes in which a handgun was reported to have been used increased from 2,648 to 3,685 - up 40 per cent. Their use was at its highest level since 1993.
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">(http://www.portal.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml;$sessionid$EMZDW4A31HRQRQFIQMGSFGGAVCBQWIV0?xml=/news/2001/07/17/nhand17.xml)</span>
<br />

<br />
Britain's crime rate has skyrocketed-- many attributing this to be due to victim and police disarmarment.
<br />

<br />
Like Australia, Britain's gun control has increased crime, not lowered it.
<br />

<br />
In the US, meanwhile, crime has dropped dramatically.  More and more states have adopted carry-concealed permits.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
The police in Orlando, FL, responded to a rape epidemic by embarking on a program to train 2,500 women in firearm use. Next year rape fell by 88 percent in Orlando.(Congressional Record, 99th Cong., 2d sess., January 30, 1968, p1496, n. 7) 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Seemingly paradoxically, the areas with the highest crime rate in the US, have the most stringent gun control.
<br />

<br />
Correspondingly, those with the least gun control, have the lowest crime rate.
<br />

<br />
My native Montana has an 80% ownership rate of guns, and yet despite this, has a lower crime rate than Canada, and has some of the most liberal gun laws in the country.
<br />

<br />
The simple truth is, as science proves, gun control does not lower crime.
<br />

<br />
The solution for reducing crime is actually much more involved, which many people don't like to think about.  It is difficult to reduce a criminal's motive to commit crime, but it is possible.
<br />

<br />
It has been shown that most violent crime is drug, or alcohol related.  If someone is already buying shipments of illegal crack cocaine, it isn't much of a stretch for them to purchase a gun from the drug dealer either, regardless of the nation's gun laws.  That is why Britain and Australia's crime rates have increased.
<br />

<br />
It is not the privately, legally held guns that are used in crime-- it is the illegally held ones.
<br />

<br />
Let's go back to this case in point: this crime that we are all concerned with took place in California.  California, despite having some of the nation's most stringent gun laws, also has an exceptionally high crime rate.
<br />

<br />
In California, by definition, this handgun was illegally possessed.  When men have such little regard for human life they'd kill someone looking at their girlfriend, or merely a passer-by, they certainly won't obey gun laws that keep honest people honest.  And this is what has been proven as I mentioned above.
<br />

<br />
There is no quick fix for the problems of crime in our society.  It's a deep-rooted, multifaceted issue, that cannot easily be solved.  Certainly, we should try, but continuing the failed social experiment of gun control will not help.
<br />

<br />
Sometimes the greatest harm results from the best of intentions.  This is one of those cases.
<br />

<br />
Make no mistake, any time someone dies an untimely death is a tragedy.  I hope this story isn't true, but it very well may be.  I certainly understand and agree with everyone's desire to try to prevent such things in the future.  But insulting gun owners and saying they have "small dicks", and letting passion rule reason, and ignoring the proof at hand will not help.
<br />

<br />
If there is anything to be learned from crimes like this, it is that at any times we can lose someone dear to us, and sometimes we never realize what someone means to us until they are gone.  It's easy to want to play the blame game, especially with 'evil' guns, but after examining the facts of the matter I think we'd be wiser to instead reflect on those who we have lost and treasure those friends we still have.
<br />

<br />
We can never fully prevent crime-- but in order to help do so, we must take an objective and scientific look at the facts of the matter and only pursue those things that will actually help us as a society at avoiding tragic losses in the future.  Gun control and calling gun owners people with small dicks just isn't one of them.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
