				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
It's an erronious assumption, especially considering that you're saying I said something I never said. The closest thing I said to that was that no one needs a gun, which is true... no one NEEDS a gun. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Fair enough, but what is <span style="font-weight: bold">need</span>?
<br />

<br />
No one <span style="font-weight: bold">needs</span> a car.
<br />
No one <span style="font-weight: bold">needs</span> alcohol.
<br />
No one <span style="font-weight: bold">needs</span> a computer.
<br />

<br />
People merely <span style="font-weight: bold">need</span> food, water, air, and shelter.
<br />

<br />
Of course, no one <span style="font-weight: bold">needs</span> to advocate gun control if it doesn't reduce crime, either.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
The burden of proof is on your shoulders in this discussion, not mine. If you're using facts you got to prove someone wrong it's your job to fully understand those facts and explain them to their fullest... not mine. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I've shown in multiple places to the best extent and nature of the statistics that areas with ultra stringent gun control's crime rates only rise.  Given the nature of the beast, I'm not sure what more you were expecting.
<br />

<br />
Also, I'd hope that people who are against private ownership of guns actually feel they have some burden of proof to restrict a right such as that.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
When one child takes out his dad's gun and kills another child, that's an accidently death too you know.
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Accidental or negligant?
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
It actually shows a steady decrease in gun-related deaths over 8, yes 8 years. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
And yet the crime and homicide rates still rise, perhaps as a result of victim disarmament.  Of course, as you mention, there are so many variables that cannot be eliminated it's hard to tell.
<br />

<br />
I can also show you facts and figures of crime and homicide dropping in areas that adopt liberal shall-issue carry concealed permit laws.
<br />

<br />
You could argue that perhaps it was due to something else that the crime and homicide rate dropped, which is fine.
<br />

<br />
But bottomline, it comes down to this:
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">1.  Gun control increases crime</span>
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">2.  Gun control has no or statistically insignificant effect on crime</span>
<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">3.  Gun control decreases crime</span>
<br />

<br />
The only reasonable interpretation you can make is one of the latter two; when you adopt draconian gun control laws and the crime and homicide rates go <span style="font-weight: bold">up</span>, you're going to have a terribly difficult time of convincing anyone that gun control works.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
You're very good at making long posts, but your statistical interpretation needs some serious work, along with your attention to detail.
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
How exactly should I be interpreting draconian gun control laws coinciding with a rise in homicide and crime?  If gun control worked, why the hell are the numbers going up, rather than down?
<br />

<br />
And why, when you give people carry concealed permits, do they go down?  Unrelated or correlated?
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
BTW in your chart you highlight one of 5 years, you fail to mention that after 97' Homicide decreased up until 1999 where it shot up, then started going down again.
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Let's look at it from a percentage perspective.
<br />

<br />
1995	356	-8%
<br />
1996	350	-9%
<br />
1997	360	-7%
<br />
1998	332	-14%
<br />
1999	386	0%
<br />
2000	346	-10%
<br />
2001	340	-12%
<br />

<br />
Is the difference a trend or is it statistically insignificant?
<br />

<br />
You tell me.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
