Ahh.  I am a programmer professionally, and yet, without computers I would still be able to live.  It all goes back to the definition of <span style="font-style: italic">need</span>.  Here in Montana, many people derive their livelyhood from hunting (guiding), etc, so it could be said a gun is to their jobs as a computer is to ours.
<br />

<br />
Anyway, the "need" thing is kind of a silly argument, because you can just as easily argue, "prove to me why you *need* to take it away" and that becomes rather difficult in things like this.
<br />

<br />
If you define need as "need to survive", then in most cases, no, they're not needed, but neither are cars, computers, etc.  It's possible to survive without them.
<br />

<br />
If you define need as "need for livelihood", then many people's livelihoods depend on them (at least in Montana here), and there certainly doesn't appear to be much, if any, homicide rate reduction from removing them.  So it would seem that guns are as essential to livelihood as anything.
<br />

<br />
I believe in personal freedom, and don't really support most gun control, or crap like the patriot act or DMCA.  I think if you're going to take away freedoms from someone, I think you'd better have a damned good reason, and gun control's "success" is so elusive if present at all that it just isn't a compelling reason to me.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
There are infinite number of factors that could be contributing to it, and unless you can prove to me specifically that it was related to gun control you have not a single limb to stand on. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Yes, I understand it's impossible to prove a cause-and-effect relationship as you state, but what you need to understand is that it's a two-way street.  By the same token that you cannot show anything more than a casual relation between gun control and homicide rate increases, you can't show a cause-and-effect relationship between gun control and homicide / crime rate decreases, nor can you even show the casual relationship.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
Additionally you do comprehend the fact that there are different aspects of "gun control" correct? Gun control isn't simply just "ban it all." I for example do not feel a "ban it all" policy is needed. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
"No one needs to own a gun for anything other than hunting" is a very different philosophy than the one I have.
<br />

<br />
And wouldn't you agree with me that the only gun control that should be adopted is reasonable provisions that can be proven to have an effect?
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
I do feel though that giving someone a very lethal weapon should be taken much more seriously than it is. 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
This sounds different from agreeing with the Australian perspective in one thread and saying only hunters need guns in this one.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
"The percentage of homicides committed with a firearm continued its declining trend since 1969."
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Indeed, but there's nothing even vaguely resembling compelling evidence that would suggest that's due to gun control.
<br />

<br />
If you destroy such a huge number of guns as Australia has done, and yet drugs, gangs etc don't change much, you'd expect crime and homicide to drop sharply, wouldn't you?
<br />

<br />
You'd expect the removal of that many guns from the civiliation population to have *some* measurable effect on how many homicides were committed... right?
<br />

<br />
Is that unreasonable?</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
